'Eric Morecambe? He'd be funny if he ditched Ernie Wise'
BBC comedy producer predicted Eric Morecambe would only find success "if he could be detached from Ernie Wise", according to a letter from the archives.
Eric Morecambe and Ernie Wise Photo: Rex	11:52AM GMT 02 Dec 2012
Comments
Eric Morecambe would only make it in comedy if he ditched Ernie Wise and went solo - the verdict of a BBC executive who laughed off the idea of them becoming television stars.
A letter unearthed in the BBC archives reveals that Wise was considered the weak link in the comedy pairing.
It was written in 1959 by John Ammonds, a producer who had seen them on stage and worked with them on radio broadcasts.
At the time, Morecambe and Wise had made one short-lived TV show for the BBC, Running Wild, which was panned by critics when it was broadcast in 1954.
“After seeing Morecambe and Wise the other week in their show [in] Blackpool, I am not at all sure as to their strength on a TV programme,” Ammonds wrote to a scriptwriter friend.
