Tough rhetoric over 'bogus students threatening UK universities'
Ministers were last night accused of harming the reputation of British universities over their increasingly tough rhetoric on student immigration.
Overseas students felt no longer welcome and were instead choosing to visit North America or Australia, it was claimed. Photo: ALAMY	By Telegraph Reporters
6:30AM GMT 09 Jan 2013
Follow Comments linked with an announcement on a new “bogus students” crackdown threatened the country’s multi-billion university sector, according to group that represents British universities. They suggested that overseas students were no longer welcome and were potentially deterring thousands of the best minds from studying in Britain, who were instead choosing to visit North America or Australia, it was claimed. Last month Theresa May, the Home Secretary, announced that consular staff would interview more than 100,000 prospective students in an attempt to prevent bogus applicants entering the country. "We are concerned about the language and the atmosphere that is being created, not least because it plays very, very badly internationally," said Nicola Dandridge, chief executive of Universities UK. "Whatever the intentions of the politicians are … every time these sorts of comments are made by the home secretary or others it does have a potentially very damaging impact internationally. Related Articles
