Conservative Party Conference: forces budget will fall below Nato minimum Britain's defence budget is likely to fall below the Nato minimum as a result of spending cuts, William Hague has admitted.
William Hague said that, once the costs of the Afghanistan operation were included, defence spending would 'get back pretty much' to 2 per cent Photo: AFP/GETTY	By James Kirkup 9:00AM BST 07 Oct 2010
It could be less than 2 per cent of gross domestic product, the minimum that alliance members are asked to spend on their militaries, the Foreign Secretary said.
Britain is one of just a handful of Nato members that meet the standard, but defence officials believe spending could fall as low as 1.7 per cent.
The United States routinely spends more than 4 per cent on defence and its officials have expressed fears about Britain's future ability to work with US forces. But Mr Hague told Radio 4: "When you face a financial crisis of this magnitude such figures are not sacrosanct."
He said that, once the costs of the Afghanistan operation were included, defence spending would "get back pretty much" to 2 per cent.
Mr Hague is a member of the National Security Council, which will start deciding today which major projects will be scrapped as part of the Strategic Defence and Security Review. Despite growing signs that the Treasury will water down its initial demand to cut the defence budget by a tenth, the Armed Forces still face the loss of some capabilities.
